==English==

===Etymology===
* First attested probably in 1472. 
* From {{etyl|frm}} {{term|absurdité|lang=frm}}, from {{etyl|LL.}} {{term|absurditas||dissonance, incongruitylang=la}}, from {{etyl|la}} {{term|absurdus|lang=la}}.
* {{suffix|absurd|ity}}

===Pronunciation===
{{a|US}} {{IPA|/əb.ˈsɝd.ət.i/|/əb.ˈzɝd.ət.i/}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|absurdities|-}}

# {{uncountable}} The quality of being absurd or [[inconsistent]] with [[obvious]] truth, reason, or sound judgment.
#* The '''absurdity''' of the actual idea of an infinite number. - [[w:John Locke|John Locke]]
#* {{RQ:Schuster Hepaticae V|viii}}
#*: Neither [Jones]{{...}} nor I (in 1966) could conceive of reducing our "science" to the ultimate '''absurdity''' of reading Finnish newspapers almost a century and a half old in order to establish "priority."
# {{countable}} That which is absurd; an absurd action; a [[logical]] [[contradiction]].
#* His travels were full of '''absurdities'''. - Johnson

